{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512297"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:53:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:53:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11873"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11873"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.17,0.7,0.06,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52866"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4473"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11873"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38246"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"},{"type":"tags","id":"4614"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6543"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6722"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44713"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52866"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after collapsing on day eight following an elective right total hip replacement for osteoarthritis. His post-operative course has been complicated by pain, and he has been uncooperative with staff, refusing to mobilise out of bed. For the past two days, he had been complaining of lower leg pain and swelling, which was not investigated. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications other than post-operative analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is unresponsive and not breathing. His pulse rate is undetectable, blood pressure is unmeasurable, respiratory rate is 0/min, and SpO2 is unrecordable. Cardiopulmonary resuscitation is initiated immediately. Bag-valve-mask ventilation is commenced with 15 L of oxygen, and a manual defibrillator is attached to the patient. The electrocardiogram reveals pulseless electrical activity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer 300 mg amiodarone intravenously","Deliver a defibrillation shock","Administer 1 mg adrenaline intravenously","Administer 0.5 mg adrenaline intramuscularly to the lateral thigh","Administer 10 mL/kg normal saline bolus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is in cardiac arrest with pulseless electrical activity (PEA), which is a \u0027non-shockable\u0027 rhythm. The immediate management of PEA in advanced life support is to administer \u003Cstrong\u003E1 mg of adrenaline intravenously\u003C/strong\u003E. This dose should be repeated every 3-5 minutes or after every second \u0027loop\u0027 of two minutes of CPR and rhythm re-analysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelivering a defibrillation shock\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for PEA. Defibrillation is only indicated for \u0027shockable\u0027 rhythms, which include ventricular fibrillation and pulseless ventricular tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering 300 mg amiodarone intravenously\u003C/strong\u003E is not the correct first step for PEA. Amiodarone is used in the \u0027shockable\u0027 pathway of the advanced life support algorithm and is typically given after three unsuccessful shocks have been administered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering 0.5 mg adrenaline intramuscularly to the lateral thigh\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended initial treatment for anaphylaxis in adults, not for cardiac arrest. In cardiac arrest, intravenous access is preferred for medication administration when available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering 10 mL/kg normal saline bolus\u003C/strong\u003E is not the priority in this situation. While fluid resuscitation may be considered in PEA, especially if hypovolaemia is suspected, it is not the first-line treatment. The immediate priority is to administer adrenaline and continue high-quality CPR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that this patient\u0027s presentation raises suspicion for a pulmonary embolism as the cause of the cardiac arrest, given his recent surgery, immobility, and lower leg symptoms. However, the immediate management remains the same regardless of the suspected cause. Once return of spontaneous circulation is achieved, further investigation and management of the underlying cause should be pursued.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["\u0027Non-shockable\u0027 rhythms are pulseless electrical activity and asystole.","\u0027Shockable\u0027 rhythms include ventricular fibrillation and pulseless ventricular tachycardia.","When a \u0027non-shockable\u0027 rhythm is identified during advanced life support, a 1 mg adrenaline IV dose should be given immediately."],"references":["Advanced Life Support Level 1. 3rd ed. Melbourne: Australian Resuscitation Council; 2016.","Adult advanced life support. In: ANZCOR guidelines [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.anzcor.org/home/adult-advanced-life-support/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38246"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11873"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38246"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-11T09:55:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-11T10:15:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4473"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52866"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"dat